[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:06.888 --> 00:00:21.122 align:middle line:90%


00:00:21.122 --> 00:00:22.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA GARR: Hi,
this is Lisa Garr,

00:00:22.580 --> 00:00:24.130 align:middle line:90%
host of "Gaiam Inspirations."

00:00:24.130 --> 00:00:26.470 align:middle line:84%
We are coming to you live
from Boulder, Colorado

00:00:26.470 --> 00:00:28.390 align:middle line:84%
at the Gaiam studios
here in Boulder.

00:00:28.390 --> 00:00:32.740 align:middle line:84%
So today, we're talking about
stress and how to reduce it.

00:00:32.740 --> 00:00:35.560 align:middle line:10%
And we're going to be doing some
exercises later on in the show

00:00:35.560 --> 00:00:39.550 align:middle line:10%
specifically about how
to obtain coherence

00:00:39.550 --> 00:00:41.843 align:middle line:10%
and also how to reduce
stress in your life.

00:00:41.843 --> 00:00:44.260 align:middle line:10%
We're going to be talking about
the scientific connections

00:00:44.260 --> 00:00:45.730 align:middle line:10%
between the heart and the brain.

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:47.380 align:middle line:90%
Joining me is Howard Martin.

00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:49.900 align:middle line:84%
He's the executive vice
president of HeartMath.

00:00:49.900 --> 00:00:52.840 align:middle line:84%
He's also the author of
"The HeartMath Solution."

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:55.210 align:middle line:84%
And he's on the steering
committee for the Global

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:56.385 align:middle line:90%
Coherence Initiative.

00:00:56.385 --> 00:00:58.010 align:middle line:84%
Thank you so much
for joining me today.

00:00:58.010 --> 00:00:58.420 align:middle line:84%
>>HOWARD MARTIN:
Well, Lisa, it's

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:01.030 align:middle line:84%
a pleasure to be here with
you in the Gaiam studios

00:01:01.030 --> 00:01:02.980 align:middle line:84%
out here in the beautiful snow
covered Rocky Mountains today.

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:03.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I know.

00:01:03.210 --> 00:01:04.340 align:middle line:90%
It's beautiful out today.

00:01:04.340 --> 00:01:05.379 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: It's been a great day.

00:01:05.379 --> 00:01:06.921 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is what
stress is about.

00:01:06.921 --> 00:01:08.380 align:middle line:90%
It's about anxiety.

00:01:08.380 --> 00:01:11.560 align:middle line:10%
It's about things crashing that
you are out of control with.

00:01:11.560 --> 00:01:14.000 align:middle line:10%
There's a lot of things
that go along with stress.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.575 align:middle line:10%
So exactly what does
stress do to the body?

00:01:16.575 --> 00:01:17.950 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well,
it's debilitating

00:01:17.950 --> 00:01:19.000 align:middle line:90%
really, too much stress.

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:20.833 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we can have a
certain natural amount

00:01:20.833 --> 00:01:22.600 align:middle line:90%
of stress in life.

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:24.250 align:middle line:10%
But if it's ongoing,
if it's chronic,

00:01:24.250 --> 00:01:26.230 align:middle line:10%
it's very debilitating
to health.

00:01:26.230 --> 00:01:28.060 align:middle line:10%
Stress releases
hormones into our body

00:01:28.060 --> 00:01:30.490 align:middle line:10%
that, in excessive amounts,
just aren't good for us.

00:01:30.490 --> 00:01:32.407 align:middle line:10%
Things like cortisol
and adrenaline,

00:01:32.407 --> 00:01:34.240 align:middle line:10%
too much of that's just
not a healthy thing.

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:35.570 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: And then you
burn out the adrenals,

00:01:35.570 --> 00:01:37.720 align:middle line:10%
and you go into the fight or--
it's like we're constantly

00:01:37.720 --> 00:01:38.800 align:middle line:10%
in fear of the tiger.

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:39.842 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: That's correct.

00:01:39.842 --> 00:01:41.920 align:middle line:84%
And the nervous system,
autonomic nervous system

00:01:41.920 --> 00:01:45.160 align:middle line:90%
goes into a state of fatigue.

00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:47.410 align:middle line:84%
That leads to a host of
other medical problems.

00:01:47.410 --> 00:01:48.880 align:middle line:84%
And then at a
psychological level,

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:52.128 align:middle line:84%
really, I think it's robbing
us of the quality of life.

00:01:52.128 --> 00:01:54.670 align:middle line:84%
We live in a society today when
there's just a lot of stress.

00:01:54.670 --> 00:01:56.260 align:middle line:84%
And it's unavoidable
in some ways.

00:01:56.260 --> 00:01:59.325 align:middle line:84%
But there are things we can
do to reduce it in other ways.

00:01:59.325 --> 00:02:01.450 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: What are some of
the main sources of stress

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:02.325 align:middle line:10%
that I'm seeing here?

00:02:02.325 --> 00:02:04.463 align:middle line:10%
What are the ways that
people experience stress?

00:02:04.463 --> 00:02:06.130 align:middle line:10%
>>MARTIN: Well, there's
two major things

00:02:06.130 --> 00:02:07.990 align:middle line:10%
that show up in most
stress surveys as number

00:02:07.990 --> 00:02:08.790 align:middle line:10%
one and number two.

00:02:08.790 --> 00:02:12.262 align:middle line:10%
The first one is the feeling
of not having enough time.

00:02:12.262 --> 00:02:13.720 align:middle line:84%
And I think if
you're anybody who's

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:15.020 align:middle line:90%
listening can relate to that.

00:02:15.020 --> 00:02:16.690 align:middle line:84%
Does it feel like you just
can't get it all done?

00:02:16.690 --> 00:02:17.680 align:middle line:90%
There's not enough time.

00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:18.638 align:middle line:90%
There's too much to do.

00:02:18.638 --> 00:02:21.310 align:middle line:84%
This person's comment was my
workload has doubled, you know,

00:02:21.310 --> 00:02:22.330 align:middle line:90%
for example.

00:02:22.330 --> 00:02:23.622 align:middle line:90%
These are things that are real.

00:02:23.622 --> 00:02:25.420 align:middle line:84%
So that feeling of not
having enough time.

00:02:25.420 --> 00:02:28.525 align:middle line:84%
The second is the feeling
of not being in control.

00:02:28.525 --> 00:02:30.650 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: The feeling of not
having choices and not--

00:02:30.650 --> 00:02:30.790 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Yeah.

00:02:30.790 --> 00:02:32.080 align:middle line:84%
Your world is spinning
out of control.

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:32.920 align:middle line:90%
I can't control it.

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:34.120 align:middle line:84%
These things are
happening to me.

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:34.450 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's happening outside.

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:35.950 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: I can do
nothing about it.

00:02:35.950 --> 00:02:39.050 align:middle line:84%
You know, I have a job that
I hate but I can't quit.

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:41.440 align:middle line:84%
These are examples of
just not having control.

00:02:41.440 --> 00:02:44.560 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's also the global
economic situation and what

00:02:44.560 --> 00:02:46.840 align:middle line:84%
we're dealing with in our
political environments

00:02:46.840 --> 00:02:47.300 align:middle line:90%
and so forth.

00:02:47.300 --> 00:02:48.010 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:02:48.010 --> 00:02:50.593 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: The thing about stress
is people sometimes don't see

00:02:50.593 --> 00:02:52.390 align:middle line:84%
is that it's not just
the external things.

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:55.300 align:middle line:84%
It's our perception of external
things that create the stress.

00:02:55.300 --> 00:02:57.760 align:middle line:84%
But more importantly, this
is where it gets interesting,

00:02:57.760 --> 00:02:59.440 align:middle line:84%
it's the emotional
reactions we are

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:03.442 align:middle line:84%
having to the perceptions
that we're having of stress.

00:03:03.442 --> 00:03:05.650 align:middle line:84%
So I just said that the two
major things that show up

00:03:05.650 --> 00:03:07.300 align:middle line:84%
on surveys as a
source of stress are

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:10.240 align:middle line:84%
the feeling of not
having enough time

00:03:10.240 --> 00:03:11.980 align:middle line:84%
and the feeling of
not being in control.

00:03:11.980 --> 00:03:14.020 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Well, then
Anthony here on Twitter

00:03:14.020 --> 00:03:18.670 align:middle line:10%
basically says that it is
real, that people are laid off

00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:21.380 align:middle line:10%
and that he is doing
the work of 10 people.

00:03:21.380 --> 00:03:22.553 align:middle line:90%
That's real.

00:03:22.553 --> 00:03:23.470 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: That's real.

00:03:23.470 --> 00:03:24.860 align:middle line:90%
So he can't change that.

00:03:24.860 --> 00:03:27.318 align:middle line:84%
The one thing that he can change
is his emotional reactions

00:03:27.318 --> 00:03:28.118 align:middle line:90%
to it.

00:03:28.118 --> 00:03:29.630 align:middle line:84%
You know, what is
he feeling inside?

00:03:29.630 --> 00:03:30.550 align:middle line:90%
Not saying that's easy.

00:03:30.550 --> 00:03:33.008 align:middle line:84%
I have tremendous compassion
for Anthony and all the people

00:03:33.008 --> 00:03:34.750 align:middle line:84%
out there who are
going through a lot

00:03:34.750 --> 00:03:36.400 align:middle line:90%
of extra stress in their life.

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:38.410 align:middle line:90%
It's endemic of our time.

00:03:38.410 --> 00:03:40.807 align:middle line:84%
And at the same time,
that's the solution really.

00:03:40.807 --> 00:03:42.640 align:middle line:84%
We're not going to
change all the externals.

00:03:42.640 --> 00:03:44.890 align:middle line:84%
We're in this high speed
era right now where

00:03:44.890 --> 00:03:46.070 align:middle line:90%
things are very volatile.

00:03:46.070 --> 00:03:47.980 align:middle line:84%
So we're not going to be able
to change all these things.

00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:50.415 align:middle line:84%
Our best option is to learn
to change from the inside out.

00:03:50.415 --> 00:03:51.790 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What is
the significance?

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:53.440 align:middle line:84%
And how does heart
play into all of this?

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:55.630 align:middle line:84%
What's that connection between
the heart and the brain?

00:03:55.630 --> 00:03:57.588 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well, our work
at HeartMath for years

00:03:57.588 --> 00:03:59.620 align:middle line:84%
is really implementing
a heart-based system

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:02.650 align:middle line:84%
consisting of methods,
tools, and technology

00:04:02.650 --> 00:04:05.330 align:middle line:84%
all designed to empower people
during these changing times.

00:04:05.330 --> 00:04:06.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh good.

00:04:06.130 --> 00:04:06.910 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: It's what we do there.

00:04:06.910 --> 00:04:08.035 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's what we
need, empowerment, yes.

00:04:08.035 --> 00:04:09.310 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: That's exactly what
we've been doing for 20 years

00:04:09.310 --> 00:04:10.110 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:04:10.110 --> 00:04:11.903 align:middle line:84%
And heart's been
around for a long time

00:04:11.903 --> 00:04:12.820 align:middle line:90%
if you think about it.

00:04:12.820 --> 00:04:14.195 align:middle line:84%
Thousands of years,
people talked

00:04:14.195 --> 00:04:17.410 align:middle line:84%
about heart and referenced
heart in these glowing ways.

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:19.720 align:middle line:84%
And yet, in modern
society, we often

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:21.459 align:middle line:84%
find ourselves
disconnected from that,

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:23.140 align:middle line:84%
sort of living life
from the neck up

00:04:23.140 --> 00:04:24.910 align:middle line:90%
of what heart really is.

00:04:24.910 --> 00:04:27.440 align:middle line:84%
So to me, what heart
is it's physiological.

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:29.860 align:middle line:84%
We certainly know about its
cardiovascular function.

00:04:29.860 --> 00:04:31.443 align:middle line:84%
And I'll share some
things in a minute

00:04:31.443 --> 00:04:33.430 align:middle line:84%
about what it does at
a physiological level

00:04:33.430 --> 00:04:35.380 align:middle line:90%
that people don't realize.

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:37.150 align:middle line:90%
It's also an emotional heart.

00:04:37.150 --> 00:04:39.360 align:middle line:84%
The words like love,
care, compassion--

00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:40.160 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Gratitude.

00:04:40.160 --> 00:04:41.500 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: --gratitude,
appreciation--

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:42.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's my favorite.

00:04:42.010 --> 00:04:44.710 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: --those things always
come fit together with heart.

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:47.240 align:middle line:84%
So there's an emotional side
of what heart really is.

00:04:47.240 --> 00:04:49.240 align:middle line:84%
There's a spiritual
connection that we have that

00:04:49.240 --> 00:04:51.610 align:middle line:84%
comes through heart where we
really connect to something

00:04:51.610 --> 00:04:53.110 align:middle line:90%
larger than our ordinary self.

00:04:53.110 --> 00:04:55.960 align:middle line:84%
And it comes in through
really to me from heart.

00:04:55.960 --> 00:04:59.020 align:middle line:84%
And taken back around,
it's that part of us where

00:04:59.020 --> 00:05:00.940 align:middle line:90%
our authentic self comes from.

00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:04.000 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is the thing
that reduces the stress here

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:05.583 align:middle line:84%
is getting in contact
with that space.

00:05:05.583 --> 00:05:06.542 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: That's right.

00:05:06.542 --> 00:05:07.810 align:middle line:90%
It's an intelligence we have.

00:05:07.810 --> 00:05:10.140 align:middle line:84%
We call it heart
intelligence at HeartMath.

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:11.590 align:middle line:84%
It's this magnificent
intelligence

00:05:11.590 --> 00:05:12.770 align:middle line:90%
that we were all born with.

00:05:12.770 --> 00:05:14.050 align:middle line:90%
It's there all the time.

00:05:14.050 --> 00:05:15.370 align:middle line:90%
We get disconnected from it.

00:05:15.370 --> 00:05:17.500 align:middle line:84%
We start living our
life from the neck up.

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:19.420 align:middle line:84%
We cut ourselves
off from something

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:21.520 align:middle line:84%
that's part of who we are
and essential to living

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:23.117 align:middle line:84%
a meaningful and
fulfilling life.

00:05:23.117 --> 00:05:25.450 align:middle line:84%
The methods, techniques, and
things we have at HeartMath

00:05:25.450 --> 00:05:27.710 align:middle line:84%
are just designed to
reconnect you with that.

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:29.665 align:middle line:84%
And when you do, life
can get better quicker.

00:05:29.665 --> 00:05:33.130 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you ever notice where
you're traveling around or even

00:05:33.130 --> 00:05:35.350 align:middle line:84%
looking if you go
to a restaurant,

00:05:35.350 --> 00:05:36.763 align:middle line:90%
everyone's on their phones.

00:05:36.763 --> 00:05:38.680 align:middle line:84%
And they're just looking
at this device, which

00:05:38.680 --> 00:05:40.660 align:middle line:84%
has so many fun
bells and whistles,

00:05:40.660 --> 00:05:42.670 align:middle line:84%
instead of connecting
to each other.

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:45.520 align:middle line:84%
If people are standing in
an unfamiliar environment,

00:05:45.520 --> 00:05:47.770 align:middle line:90%
it's like an instant reaction.

00:05:47.770 --> 00:05:51.100 align:middle line:84%
Rather than connecting and
communicating with humans,

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:55.360 align:middle line:84%
which might be dangerous
and I don't know ,

00:05:55.360 --> 00:05:57.345 align:middle line:84%
it's the instant
defense mechanism.

00:05:57.345 --> 00:05:58.720 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: That's
just one example

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:00.270 align:middle line:84%
of the way we are
living our lives now.

00:06:00.270 --> 00:06:00.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:01.870 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: It's not
necessarily all bad.

00:06:01.870 --> 00:06:03.310 align:middle line:84%
But I'm just saying
it's part of the habits

00:06:03.310 --> 00:06:04.450 align:middle line:90%
that we've developed.

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:06.400 align:middle line:84%
But many people now are
getting on to the fact

00:06:06.400 --> 00:06:08.740 align:middle line:84%
that they can't go on living
the ways in which they've

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:09.440 align:middle line:90%
been living.

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:10.648 align:middle line:90%
And that's actually positive.

00:06:10.648 --> 00:06:11.710 align:middle line:90%
That's motivation.

00:06:11.710 --> 00:06:14.260 align:middle line:84%
That's part of this era
that's been generically called

00:06:14.260 --> 00:06:15.740 align:middle line:90%
by many the shift.

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:17.170 align:middle line:84%
As people are
starting to change,

00:06:17.170 --> 00:06:19.270 align:middle line:84%
starting to want
things to be different,

00:06:19.270 --> 00:06:21.760 align:middle line:84%
starting to develop new
capacities within themselves to

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:23.980 align:middle line:84%
manifest the changes
that they want.

00:06:23.980 --> 00:06:26.050 align:middle line:84%
So it's a time, as I
said, of great opportunity

00:06:26.050 --> 00:06:28.470 align:middle line:84%
as well as all these
challenges that we face.

00:06:28.470 --> 00:06:30.418 align:middle line:84%
I'm both a pragmatist
and an optimist.

00:06:30.418 --> 00:06:31.960 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So the heart
has a frequency.

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:34.180 align:middle line:84%
And the frequency
communicates from the heart

00:06:34.180 --> 00:06:36.200 align:middle line:84%
to the brain, the
heart to the brain.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:40.910 align:middle line:84%
And this is the place where
the coherence is potentially

00:06:40.910 --> 00:06:41.710 align:middle line:90%
achieved, right?

00:06:41.710 --> 00:06:43.335 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: So at
Institute of HeartMath,

00:06:43.335 --> 00:06:45.243 align:middle line:84%
and the brilliant
researchers we have there

00:06:45.243 --> 00:06:46.660 align:middle line:84%
for years have
been doing research

00:06:46.660 --> 00:06:49.570 align:middle line:84%
understanding the heart's
role beyond its cardiovascular

00:06:49.570 --> 00:06:50.530 align:middle line:90%
function.

00:06:50.530 --> 00:06:53.060 align:middle line:84%
And their research
combined with research

00:06:53.060 --> 00:06:55.060 align:middle line:84%
that they found scattered
in research literature

00:06:55.060 --> 00:06:57.560 align:middle line:84%
around the world that's painted
a really interesting picture

00:06:57.560 --> 00:06:59.700 align:middle line:84%
of what heart at a
physical level is.

00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:02.470 align:middle line:84%
It's an information
processing center in our body.

00:07:02.470 --> 00:07:03.710 align:middle line:90%
It communicates with us.

00:07:03.710 --> 00:07:04.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Not the brain?

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:05.800 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well,
the brain certainly

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:07.342 align:middle line:84%
is the information
processing center.

00:07:07.342 --> 00:07:08.590 align:middle line:90%
But so is the heart.

00:07:08.590 --> 00:07:10.760 align:middle line:84%
The heart sends
information to the brain

00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:11.980 align:middle line:90%
and the rest of the body.

00:07:11.980 --> 00:07:14.080 align:middle line:84%
Brain function is actually
critically dependent,

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:16.120 align:middle line:84%
for example, upon
this information.

00:07:16.120 --> 00:07:18.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it sends to the brain
instead of the brain sending

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:19.040 align:middle line:90%
to the heart?

00:07:19.040 --> 00:07:20.410 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: The brain's sending
information down to the heart,

00:07:20.410 --> 00:07:21.880 align:middle line:84%
controlling timing
of the heartbeat.

00:07:21.880 --> 00:07:23.755 align:middle line:84%
But the heart is sending
a lot of information

00:07:23.755 --> 00:07:24.790 align:middle line:90%
back to the brain.

00:07:24.790 --> 00:07:27.525 align:middle line:84%
One way it does it is through
a neurological communication.

00:07:27.525 --> 00:07:28.900 align:middle line:84%
There's actually
a nervous system

00:07:28.900 --> 00:07:31.360 align:middle line:84%
in the heart, studied
through the field of what's

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:33.220 align:middle line:90%
called neuro cardiology.

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:35.028 align:middle line:84%
It's a very sophisticated
nervous system.

00:07:35.028 --> 00:07:36.820 align:middle line:84%
It communicates with
the brain and the head

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:38.385 align:middle line:84%
through a nerve
pathway starting here

00:07:38.385 --> 00:07:40.090 align:middle line:84%
that then travels
into the brain,

00:07:40.090 --> 00:07:42.460 align:middle line:84%
terminates up our higher
perceptual thinking centers,

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:43.920 align:middle line:90%
neocortex.

00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:46.600 align:middle line:84%
And there's a constant
neurological conversation

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:48.040 align:middle line:84%
happening between
heart and brain.

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:48.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Feedback.

00:07:48.840 --> 00:07:52.420 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: When researchers map
out the neurological activity

00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:55.495 align:middle line:84%
in the body, they can see that
there's more information being

00:07:55.495 --> 00:07:57.370 align:middle line:84%
sent to the brain from
the heart than it ever

00:07:57.370 --> 00:07:59.160 align:middle line:90%
receives from the brain.

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:00.710 align:middle line:84%
And that's an
interesting phenomenon,

00:08:00.710 --> 00:08:01.450 align:middle line:90%
something I didn't know.

00:08:01.450 --> 00:08:02.350 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: More information
from the heart?

00:08:02.350 --> 00:08:04.892 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: It communicates things
like the blood pressure way.

00:08:04.892 --> 00:08:06.800 align:middle line:84%
The heart is actually
producing hormones.

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:09.490 align:middle line:84%
These are all new discoveries
showing that the heart is

00:08:09.490 --> 00:08:10.803 align:middle line:90%
doing more than pumping blood.

00:08:10.803 --> 00:08:12.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Are we
addicted to stress?

00:08:12.220 --> 00:08:14.470 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: We're addicted to
stimulation for one thing.

00:08:14.470 --> 00:08:16.720 align:middle line:84%
And many people perceive
stress as something

00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:18.730 align:middle line:84%
that you have to have,
that you won't be good

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:19.810 align:middle line:84%
if you don't have
it, that you won't

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:20.330 align:middle line:90%
perform unless you're stressed.

00:08:20.330 --> 00:08:21.010 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's a driver.

00:08:21.010 --> 00:08:21.700 align:middle line:90%
Mm-hmm.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:23.992 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: There's a term that
our founder at HeartMath,

00:08:23.992 --> 00:08:26.610 align:middle line:84%
Institute of HeartMath,
Doc Childre, has.

00:08:26.610 --> 00:08:28.450 align:middle line:84%
He says, there's a
difference between stress

00:08:28.450 --> 00:08:31.220 align:middle line:90%
and creative resistance energy.

00:08:31.220 --> 00:08:34.390 align:middle line:84%
Creative resistance energy would
be stepping up to another level

00:08:34.390 --> 00:08:37.929 align:middle line:84%
to meet a task that makes
you better, expands you

00:08:37.929 --> 00:08:41.270 align:middle line:84%
beyond your mediocrity, so that
you have some stress associated

00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:42.070 align:middle line:90%
with that.

00:08:42.070 --> 00:08:44.290 align:middle line:84%
You have something you have to
do that's unfamiliar to you,

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:46.720 align:middle line:84%
but you have to sort of go
that next level within yourself

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:48.110 align:middle line:90%
and make it happen.

00:08:48.110 --> 00:08:50.200 align:middle line:84%
That's different than
just this ongoing grind

00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:54.160 align:middle line:84%
of stress of emotional
reactions to this and that,

00:08:54.160 --> 00:08:57.190 align:middle line:84%
anxiety about things, and anger
about things, and frustration.

00:08:57.190 --> 00:08:59.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, it creates
that, as you said,

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:01.540 align:middle line:84%
cortisol reaction, which
then could stimulate you

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:02.860 align:middle line:90%
into action.

00:09:02.860 --> 00:09:05.380 align:middle line:84%
And I could see how it
could be an addiction.

00:09:05.380 --> 00:09:06.983 align:middle line:84%
You have a reaction
to something.

00:09:06.983 --> 00:09:07.900 align:middle line:90%
It creates adrenaline.

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:09.400 align:middle line:84%
And then you fight
towards that reaction.

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:10.120 align:middle line:90%
And then you fight to it.

00:09:10.120 --> 00:09:11.770 align:middle line:84%
And then you get
things done that way.

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:13.130 align:middle line:84%
And it becomes an
addictive pattern.

00:09:13.130 --> 00:09:13.270 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Sure.

00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:14.320 align:middle line:90%
But here's the way I look at it.

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:15.835 align:middle line:84%
So you can change
your emotional--

00:09:15.835 --> 00:09:17.680 align:middle line:90%
I call it your emotional diet.

00:09:17.680 --> 00:09:19.480 align:middle line:84%
People get addicted to
the stress emotions.

00:09:19.480 --> 00:09:22.820 align:middle line:84%
They get addicted to feeling
anxious or mad, things

00:09:22.820 --> 00:09:23.620 align:middle line:90%
like that.

00:09:23.620 --> 00:09:26.245 align:middle line:84%
And it's producing hormones
that they get accustomed to.

00:09:26.245 --> 00:09:28.120 align:middle line:84%
When you become more
heart-centric in the way

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:30.250 align:middle line:84%
you live, and you
begin to really feel

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:33.790 align:middle line:84%
emotions like appreciation and
gratitude and care and love

00:09:33.790 --> 00:09:35.580 align:middle line:84%
and those kind of
things, what happens

00:09:35.580 --> 00:09:39.160 align:middle line:84%
is you begin to desire those
so much more that you have

00:09:39.160 --> 00:09:42.400 align:middle line:84%
the motivation to replace those
other emotions that are more

00:09:42.400 --> 00:09:45.820 align:middle line:84%
draining, certainly harder
on your body and on your life

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:46.630 align:middle line:90%
really.

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:50.350 align:middle line:84%
And you learn to develop a
new sort of emotional diet

00:09:50.350 --> 00:09:51.700 align:middle line:90%
like what I call you know?

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:52.810 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's what we're
talking about today.

00:09:52.810 --> 00:09:53.610 align:middle line:90%
>>MARTIN: Exactly.

00:09:53.610 --> 00:09:55.260 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So what are
some of the ways

00:09:55.260 --> 00:09:59.080 align:middle line:84%
and explain the science
behind the heart's field,

00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:01.910 align:middle line:84%
that resonance that comes out
of the heart and heals us.

00:10:01.910 --> 00:10:02.710 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:10:02.710 --> 00:10:03.730 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Well, the
ways I mentioned before

00:10:03.730 --> 00:10:05.950 align:middle line:84%
about heart communicating,
its intelligence

00:10:05.950 --> 00:10:09.340 align:middle line:84%
were biological pathways,
hardwired biology.

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:12.850 align:middle line:84%
But the heart also does
things a bit differently.

00:10:12.850 --> 00:10:14.650 align:middle line:84%
And the heart is an
electrical organ.

00:10:14.650 --> 00:10:16.502 align:middle line:90%
It's an energy producing organ.

00:10:16.502 --> 00:10:18.460 align:middle line:84%
It produces by far the
source of bioelectricity

00:10:18.460 --> 00:10:21.192 align:middle line:84%
we have in our
body, 40 to 60 times

00:10:21.192 --> 00:10:22.775 align:middle line:84%
stronger than what
the brain produces.

00:10:22.775 --> 00:10:23.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:25.340 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: It goes to
every single cell.

00:10:25.340 --> 00:10:27.860 align:middle line:84%
Now the signal is strong
enough that it radiates

00:10:27.860 --> 00:10:30.500 align:middle line:84%
beyond our skin out
into space creating

00:10:30.500 --> 00:10:34.590 align:middle line:84%
an electromagnetic field that
surrounds us in 360 degrees.

00:10:34.590 --> 00:10:37.910 align:middle line:84%
Now I'm not talking about an
aura or about subtle energy.

00:10:37.910 --> 00:10:39.140 align:middle line:90%
Those things may exist.

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:40.640 align:middle line:84%
But what I'm talking
about right now

00:10:40.640 --> 00:10:43.160 align:middle line:84%
is very measurable
electromagnetic energy.

00:10:43.160 --> 00:10:45.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: An actual frequency
like a radio wave?

00:10:45.240 --> 00:10:46.340 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Like radio
waves, exactly.

00:10:46.340 --> 00:10:46.610 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:48.277 align:middle line:84%
>>MARTIN: Now this
field extends beyond.

00:10:48.277 --> 00:10:50.150 align:middle line:84%
In "The HeartMath
Solution" that I

